The fact that this place doesn’t have a perfect 5 stars is beyond me. This was my first visit and an experience I will never forget....  1. The staff from the front of the house to the back of the house were extremely friendly and knowledgeable. The chef and the manager stopped by the table to ask how the meals were being enjoyed. Though the chef could have taken all the credit he made it clear that the “team” is what made the meals so fantastic.  2.  Delia (I think that’s how you spell her name, if not please forgive me)... Anyway she was fantastic, we absolutely loved her sense of humor and her honesty when it came to making recommendations (none of which were less than AMAZING).  We never asked for anything more than once, if at all. She was on point with watching our drinks and when we were done with our plates etc.  3. I had the veal special and my date had the fish special (whole fish) I cannot remember the specific type. The veal was SOOO tender, which they describe as fall off of the bone... NO... more like so tender it’s hard to believe it’s a solid. The flavors that were put together and the pasta were just to die for. My date’s fish was nicely presented (head and all) and our wonderful waitress filleted it for us table side (and did an excellent job). Oh and of course tasted amazing as well.  4.  Everything from the house bread to the specialty drinks were made with deep thought, intent and knowledge of how to make your taste buds dance.  I left there so full but I couldn’t fathom having any extras to take home and We immediately wanted to turn around and go right back in to try something different. We haven’t been able to talk about anything else all night and will be back within the next few days to try the dishes we picked as our second choices.  5.  Without a doubt I can say that this was the best meal and service I’ve ever had in a restaurant. My date is from Italy and says that there has never been a restaurant in the US that has impressed.. until now. With that being said the prices are extremely reasonable and I would recommend this place to ANYONE who wants delish Italian and great service. I mean honestly ask yourself how many places you have been where the chef and the manager came by to see how you enjoyed the meal without a problem? I could count them on one hand.  Thank you La Scala! See you again in a few days!

La Scala is an absolute gem in Baltimore's Little Italy. The ambiance is old school romantic Italian - dim lights, exposed brick, dark wood, and white table cloths. But don't let the classic feel fool you. La Scala is anything but stuffy. The menu includes modern twists on Italian classics and the servers are friendly, knowledgeable, and eager to offer their suggestions and answer questions. In addition to their sizable printed menu, there are numerous creative and enticing specials every evening. La Scala also offers a fantastic Happy Hour at the bar, including discounted appetizers and cocktails. You can't go wrong with this spot, whether it's for a romantic evening out or a fun get together with friends. I've loved everything I've ever had to eat and drink here, but the Vitello Saltimbocca Alla Romana (veal topped with mozzarella, prosciutto, sage, and cognac sauce) is a personal favorite. If the Osso Bucco is one of the specials, don't pass it up. La Scala also has phenomenal Espresso Martinis, which make a great substitute for dessert if you are too stuffed for one of their delicious sweet options.

I was beginning to lose hope in Baltimore’s Little Italy. I grew up in philly so I know good Italian food when I taste it and after 3 attempts at a decent Italian restaurant, I regained hope with this place. The meat and cheese platters were out of this world. The meats were velvety and melt in your mouth. The bread and string beans were a nice touch. And it just kept getting better with the main course. You can’t go wrong with anything on the menu. For  dessert, we got the cream puff and the tiramisu and it was just perfect. The only opportunity area I would give this place is the ice cream selection. The only flavor they had was pistachio and as someone that is allergic to nuts, I would have liked to see a few other flavors. But everything else was out of this world. If you’re looking for a good Italian meal with a relaxed and clean atmospher for a special occasion, I recommend La Scala. Don’t waste your time anywhere else!

This used to be our absolute favorite go-to place for special occasions and to dine with friends - but our last visit was shockingly awful. We've gone many times for dinner on Sunday afternoon/early evening - they have a great small plates menu at the bar on Sundays which used to be a very nice experience and opportunity to try several different dishes and creative drinks - as well as a nice/friendly service experience. Not this time - we went two weeks ago and every dish we had was just plain bad. The calamari was tough & flavorless, and the "marinara" sauce served with it was literally watery and bland - we thought that the sauce was a mistake bc we've eaten there MANY times and always had great marinara - so we asked to please have some marinara sauce, and the bartender said that that WAS the marinara. Are you kidding me?? This is one of the top restaurants in the city and the marinara sauce literally was a bland light reddish watery broth consistency with little sign of tomatoes - and zero flavor. We tried another plate suggested by the bartender and were told it was on the happy hour menu - it was bland and room temperature, and to top it off when we got the bill it was $16 for a tiny bit of flavorless food - instead of the happy hour price as were were told. On top of this, the mixed drinks were bad bc the tonic and soda had no carbonation - and the bartender was not at all friendly as is usually the case when we eat at the bar. Also, there was an odd very loud Hispanic type of music playing in the place which was too loud and just all wrong for the normal ambiance of this restaurant. I have nothing against diverse music but this is an upscale italian restaurant, and it was out of place. Usually when we've had dinner in the bar area on Sundays the owner is there and chats with patrons, and is visibly overseeing things - we've talked to him many times over the years and he's a very nice man. He was not around the day we were there - and you would hate to think that the staff can't function without the owner there, but we wondered if that was the issue. Everything was off - no one was friendly, the food was nasty, and the drinks & service were worse. We were so creeped out that we got the check after a couple small plates and two drinks (we would usually stay at least two hours to eat several plates and try various drinks bc they have creative drink specials on Sundays). We should've complained about the error in price on the one dishes when we got the check - but honestly, we just wanted to get out of there, so we didn't mention it. Either this place is going downhill or the staff can not handle basic operations in the absence of the owners and don't care about the quality of things unless the owner is there. This is hard for us to swallow bc It's been our favorite place til now, and things were so badly off that we don't know if we'll go back. We may give it one more chance though just bc of how long we've been eating here - or we may just give Tagliatta' s a try and see if It's good enough to take Lascala' s place. What a shame. I hope it's just an off day - but honestly even I can make better marinara by light years than what I was served.
